citation.title: Juvenile Chinook Salmon Movement, Growth, Survival, and Outmigration Timing in the Chena River, Alaska

resourceInfo.abstract:
Chinook Salmon *Oncorhynchus tshawytscha* are anadromous salmonids that typically spend one year in freshwater systems before smolting. Within the Yukon River basin, the Chena River watershed is a major producer of Chinook Salmon. The overall goal for this project was to investigate the influences of freshwater processes on juvenile Chinook Salmon size and movement, post-emergence to outmigration the following spring in the Chena River basin, Alaska. Chapter one objectives were to 1) describe movement among four key rearing areas, 2) compare size patterns and end of September mean length among rearing areas, and 3) investigate relationships among end of September mean weight, stream temperature, and discharge among years using observed and simulated data. Chapter two objectives were to 1) estimate peak outmigration dates among years, 2) investigate the effects of environmental variables on outmigration timing and catchability, 3) compare juvenile Chinook Salmon size during outmigration among years, and 4) qualitatively compare minnow and rotary screw trap sampling methods within one year. This research will help fill gaps in the overall understanding of Yukon River Chinook Salmon by establishing benchmark size, movement, and outmigration data for the Chena River basin, as well as highlight the importance of long-term monitoring of juvenile Chinook Salmon in northern rivers. Additionally, incorporating juvenile data into stock-recruitment models and growth potential models could help managers make decisions regarding escapement goals and fishery closures both in-season and long term.
The data attached to this ServCat project (code: 156066) is only that collected by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and is applicable to Chapter 2 of Edwards (2023) thesis. Juvenile Chinook Salmon data was also collected by the Alaska Department of Fish and Game in support of Edwards (2023) entire thesis project.

resourceInfo.abstract: Tabular dataset of data collected from chinook salmon smolt trapping on the Chena River in May and June of 2017-2019. Trapping took place between the East end of the Fort Wainwright airfield (N 64.831952, W -147.571279) and adjacent to Chena Marina (N 64.81065, W -147.89908) in 2017, between Hamilton Acres (N 64.839650, W -147.681000) and Pikes Landing (N 64.830467, W ‚Äì147.848750) in 2018, and between Nordale Road Bridge (N64.846536, W -147.410418) and Grahel Park (N 64.845831, W ‚Äì147.706114) in 2019. This dataset contains the total number of traps set on a given date and the total number of Chinook salmon captured on that given date.
